  "notes": {
    "mappings": [
      {
        "kind": "text",
        "value": "Equation 17 says that a small perturbation "
      },
      {
        "kind": "text",
        "value": "mu",
        "hitBox": {
          "id": "perturbation_mode",
          "label": "perturbation mode",
          "sequence": "mu of theta omega",
          "category": "function",
          "latex": "\\mu(\\theta,\\omega)"
        }
      },
      {
        "kind": "text",
        "value": " is shaped by two effects at once: advection in theta from each oscillator's own natural frequency omega, and mean-field feedback from the population average encoded by the double integral. The right-hand side lambda times mu means we are looking for perturbation modes that grow or decay exponentially in time."
      },
      {
        "kind": "text",
        "value": " This equation comes from writing the density as the incoherent state plus a small perturbation mu tilde, then setting mu tilde equals e to the lambda t times mu and ignoring terms nonlinear in mu. The accompanying normalization condition appears as Eq. 18."
      }
    ]
  },
  "footer": {
    "presentation": "freeform",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "kind": "text",
        "value": "Conceptually, Eq. 17 turns the synchronization question into an eigenvalue problem in the section Synchronization in the limit N equals infinity. You use it specifically when asking whether the incoherent state is linearly stable in the noiseless infinite-N limit. If some admissible lambda has positive real part, incoherence is unstable; if all admissible lambdas have negative real part, incoherence is linearly stable. This is a different question from the earlier self-consistency equations, which characterize synchronized branches once they exist. The eigenvalue reference expands this connection.",
        "referenceFrame": {
          "topicId": "kuramoto-eq17-eigenvalues-reference",
          "title": "Eq. 17 Eigenvalues"
        },
        "referenceLabel": "Open the eigenvalue reference"
      },
      {
        "kind": "text",
        "value": "Open a visual showing how a tiny perturbation can either decay or grow under Eq. 17.",
        "visualizationFrame": {
          "mode": "plugin",
          "pluginId": "kuramoto_eq17_linear_stability",
          "name": "Kuramoto Eq. 17 Linear Stability"
        },
        "visualizationLabel": "Open Eq. 17 stability visualization"
      }
    ]
